{"review_id":"2WvK7ex5z5uFgwDzkwpFjQ","user_id":"bq4J5CtWh7uoRb_zMD-fXQ","business_id":"vHz2RLtfUMVRPFmd7VBEHA","stars":2.0,"useful":0,"funny":0,"cool":0,"text":"Kinda wish I hadn't eaten here. \n\nFirst off, make sure to do a reservation. It was great to show up and beat the line that's waiting there. I didn't see the wait times for anyone but I didn't need to since they sat us right away. \n\nThe view was nice at our 2 person table and the decor pleasant. Where we were seated, we couldn't see the cooks so that was unfortunate. It is setup to replicate the show experience so I think sitting near the cooks puts you more into that full immersion if that's what you are desiring. \n\nThe food:\n\nThis is where it hurts. I really wanted to like the food. My wife took me here for my birthday and we are huge fans of the show and Gordon Ramsey. So when our Lobster Risotto and White Asparagus soup came out, I was expecting food bliss. What we got was small portions of bland, undercooked food. I kept eating the risotto thinking, \"What is this missing? Why is it so crunchy?\" I finally asked for salt and it made the taste better. But the salt wasn't going to help it being undercooked. The lobster was ok. Nothing miraculous. Nothing horrible. Just...ok. I think there in lies a problem. Why is a $24 item on the menu only partially ok? The soup was bland as well. Salt improved the dish putting it at a resounding ok dish as well. \n\nBeef Wellington. I was looking forward to this with lowered expectations (due to the last course) and it was....ok as well. The meat was cooked to a nice medium rare but it felt and tasted like it was mass produced (which it had to have been since everyone was ordering it). There was a white purée to the side which was good. It was seasoned so it made it stand out. The vegetables however were an after thought. It's like someone said, \"Oh crap, put some carrots on there. You don't need to cook them, just throw em some hot water so they feel warm and out then on the plate.\" They were hard and not satisfying at all. \n\nMy wife had some potatoes gratin which were not seasoned at all. At this point, we had a small jar of salt that the waiter had brought over (we asked for it). I was confused on how he didn't ask about the food at all. Just kept asking if he could assist us with anything. I felt like I was cutting my meat like a pro so I wasn't sure what assistance he could provide. \n\nDessert time. And finally something good came. The Sticky Toffee Pudding was great. Not necessarily life changing, but it was genuinely really good. It was the only thing I'd order again and eat. The portion was very generous as well. We also got the Chocolate Cake which was ok. Nothing bad, nothing great. Just....ok. \n\nLastly, the ambience. First of all, it was loud. From the music to the acoustics, it was hard to have a conversation. The waiter was trying to talk to us about the menu and we couldn't hear him at all. We enjoyed a friendly game of \"What do you think he said?\" everytime he came by to talk to us. \n\nLastly, there was this lady who would not stop screaming. Apparently she just....won a billion dollars or got married or divorced (depending on your perspective of life). Either way, she would not stop screeching for joy. It was ruining the dinner experience. So what did the staff do? Nothing meaningful. The Assistant Manager finally came over to the table and told them, \"Hey guys. You should be happy and joyful. Go for it!\" We didn't think that was super effective. And we were right. She kept screeching. Tables were getting visibly upset. The only reason any of the screeching stopped was because they left. \n\nWe paid our bill (around $150 with tip) and then asked to speak to someone about our experience. The waiter was happy to hear our critiques and was very kind. I'd like to think we were very kind to him as well. We talked about our food and our thoughts. He said he'd pass it on to the kitchen. We also shared our displeasure with how the Asst. Manager handled the screeching lady. The waiter listened to us and said he'd pass it along. The waiter did try and do something to comp us for our bad experience but we didn't want that to impact our critique. We were happy to pay full price if only so they would take our criticism to heart. \n\nUnfortunately, we will never be returning to this establishment. The only thing I'm thankful for is that I am no longer curious about how anything tastes. For that, I am grateful.","date":"2018-06-28 04:50:39"}
