{"review_id":"KHdTnwRTpY-PnMbBRsHMJQ","user_id":"oqTZC9WriodTCby6jl0LfQ","business_id":"vHz2RLtfUMVRPFmd7VBEHA","stars":5.0,"useful":4,"funny":2,"cool":3,"text":"Hubby and I decided to come to Hell's Kitchen for our first year anniversary dinner! We made our reservation three weeks in advance and still couldn't secure a decent dinner time so we settled with what we could get: 4:45 PM. It was a little early but oh well! More time to digest our food afterwards! We did get there a tiny bit late, about five minutes, and it was a-okay. No issues. We did call to let them know as well and they were very accommodating.\n\nMy husband and I decided to share:\n\nNotes From Gordon: Plymouth dry gin, green tea, lemongrass, peach, lemon, and a message from Gordon. The presentation is really nice for this cocktail because of the note. It's kind of \"cute.\" As for the taste, I can't say that it was my favorite. It had a nice fresh and light front, almost like sprite and vodka. However, as soon as that left, it tasted like cough syrup and that could be due to the gin. \n\nLobster Risotto: Butter poached lobster tail, saffron risotto, and tomato confit. Delicious, delicious, delicious. I thought it was going to be a huge portion but it wasn't, which is good! Because huge portions of risotto means it gets way too heavy. Hell's Kitchen's serving size is perfect! \n\nHeirloom Tomato Burrata Salad: Heirloom tomatoes, white balsamic reduction, olive oil, crystalized basil, and thai basil mix. Very refreshing. The heirloom tomatoes were a little sweet and the crystalized basil added an interesting texture to the mix. We had this after the risotto and I think it was perfect timing.\n\nBeef Wellington: Potato puree, glazed root vegetables, and red wine demi-glace. My husband got this dish and he loved it. He finished the whole thing! They use filet mignon for their choice of meat. The puff pastry was done super well. \n\nRoasted Rack of Lamb: Vadouvan carrots, bloomsdale spinach, and harissa lamb jus. This was my entree and I loved every bit of it. They use Colorado lamb versus New Zealand lamb for this. Colorado lamb is meatier and less gamy than New Zealand lamb. I actually don't mind the gaminess from lamb so it wasn't a point of concern. Colorado rack of lamb is definitely larger in size and despite it being meatier, it was still very tender. Their cooking method is also the reason why it would be tender. The whole rack is cooked before slicing -- they may sear it and finish it in the oven, keeping a tight control on the temperature. I wanted medium rare and that is exactly what I got!\n\nWild Mushroom Side: Ehhhh. It was good but definitely didn't add to the meal. It's one of those things where if we have it cool, if we don't cool. \n\nFor dessert, we got their sticky toffee pudding. It came with a scoop speculoos ice cream on top. It was delicious and diabetic sweet. I'm not a huge sweets fan but I couldn't stop eating this pudding! The mixture of hot and cold was great but you know what would be better? A glass of milk with it. \n\nI can't say that I am an avid Gordon Ramsey fan. I don't follow his shows religiously but I have watched snippets here and there. I also see a lot of his memes online. I have also seen some of his quick youtube videos on how to make simple yet delicious meals. I honestly believe that Hell's Kitchen is definitely a good place to dine in. Their prices are fairly reasonable and the portions are perfect. The service was great. The server even had them add a candle to our dessert to celebrate our anniversary! \n\nIf you don't have reservations, you could probably grab a seat at the bar or high tops. You could literally just walk in, have dessert and leave! \n\nI definitely wouldn't mind coming again. I have been dreaming about their Lobster Risotto since.","date":"2018-09-11 06:49:31"}
