ve and beyond your job just because you want to and that was my impression of Charlie, the waiter. The busboy and water filler (not sure of their actual titles) were so polite and patient. I saw no issues with the service from top to bottom, beginning to end. \n\nThe Food: I started the Scampi Prawns. They weren't as big as I am used to prawns being and there were a total of three. They were served in an oriental like hot plate causing the prawns to sizzle. It made me think of how fajitas are served yet this was much more sophisticated and elegant. I then moved to the NY strip steak with extra red wine demi-glace and potato gratin. The potato gratin had NO seasoning at all. I couldn't believe it. It was then I felt Gordon did not stand behind his word. Those potatoes NEEDED salt and pepper. It's like whoever prepared them figured the cheese would season the potatoes. WRONG! I was scared to ask for salt and pepper since they weren't on the table, so I added demi-glace and ate as much as I could. Even with the red wine demi-glace, the potato gratin still needed salt and pepper. Mom started with the white asparagus soup and then moved to the roasted rack of lamb. She loved the soup. They offered cracked pepper and she said it tasted better with the pepper. SF had the Beef Wellington topped with foie gras. SF is a HUGE fan of the tv show and apparently, the Beef Wellington is a thing lol. SF also loves foie gras so she indulged with a smile. Because we were celebrating both of their birthdays, mom and SF received complimentary Sticky Toffee Pudding with Speculoos ice cream. I'm blaming Charlie because I received a complimentary one as well, without the candle, haahaaa. I don't know what speculoos is but it was the ABSOLUTE BEST pairing to this sticky toffee pudding that looked like a bran muffin. THE DESSERT WAS DELICIOUS!!!!  \n\nSummation: Will I return? MOST DEFINITELY! Will I get the potato gratin? Never! Will I try something else besides the NY strip steak? Yes! I 