{"review_id":"aBF5oJ3LEihJ74cbaoL6nw","user_id":"sGJvx1MTsetDzsnrHfJHLg","business_id":"vHz2RLtfUMVRPFmd7VBEHA","stars":5.0,"useful":40,"funny":34,"cool":37,"text":"You should hate Gordon Ramsay Hell's Kitchen but you won't. \n\nCeasar's Entertainment​ needed something to fill the void of the ill-fated Serendipity​ in the flagship restaurant​ located​​ in front of Ceasar's Palace. With that in mind, they dialed up one off of the Food Network's one and only Gordon Ramsay and of course he was interested. \n\nThe exterior is an obnoxious blend of concrete​, metal, and Gordon Ramsay's face. Inside you will find more of the same. Gordon is seemingly everywhere with no less than 30 photos of himself along with a wall of every series winner from the television program that shares its​ name with this restaurant​. Gordon really is unabashed​ with the smearing his likeness anywhere it will fit in this themed restaurant​ geared for the global tourist​ set in Vegas. \n\nThe service is solid, albeit slow, particularly​ at peak times which is when you would want to visit. Even with reservations made well in advance,​ we waited patiently for over twenty minutes as a table for six was readied for us on a Saturday night. Once seated, ​however, our server was gregarious​, knowledgeable, and quick to react. \n\nIt would be remiss​ of any visitor​ to pass up on the chance to try the handcrafted cocktails available and with that in mind the men at the table ordered the Smoke on the Boulevard​ cocktail​ featuring Woodford Rye along with Aperol, Amaro Averna, and sweet Vermouth served elegantly in a glass container with Cherry Wood smoke that dazzles the senses while served. The drink itself is superb and perfectly balanced as it should be with the stiff $16.00 price tag attached to it. There is plenty​ of punch in the Rye so one is all that is necessary​ to get a solid buzz going before the cuisine starts making its way to the table. \n\nAs an appetizer,​ we shared the Oysters on a half shell and we were lucky enough to come at a time when the Kusshi varietal was in-season which sports a sweet and briny flavor and is best adorned with the provided HK MIgnonette and a dab of Gin Cocktail Sauce. A dozen will set you back roughly $40.00, so I recommend you enjoy them slowly. \n\nFor the main entree,​ I opted for Gordon's widely acclaimed Beef Wellington​ and although it takes time to prepare - it did not disappoint. A thick and expertly prepared Beef Filet is wrapped tightly in Puff Pastry and then roasted to a quintessential medium​-rare and served with Potato Puree, Glazed Root Vegetables, and the most robust Red Wine Demi-Glace I can recall in recent memory. From the quality of the meat to the delicate Puff Pastry, this is the perfect example of Beef Wellington​ and my new bar against any other. I know I am gushing here and trust it is warranted. Easily the best $50.00 I spent while I visited Las Vegas this time around. \n\nI will be fully transparent in that I wanted to loathe and scathe everything about Gordon Ramsay Hell's Kitchen from the moment I stepped through the doors but I simply cannot. Everything from the work being done in the open kitchen to the results that came from it was​ utterly remarkable​. Sure, it lacks the Michelin stars of his Chelsea​ location in England​ and is far too boisterous, but this is Vegas after all...\n\nI highly recommend.","date":"2018-07-16 14:34:10"}
