{"review_id":"ShYqHG7TI1t9JWF3x8HOBQ","user_id":"3KK7L2Q6NMfJA1Ky4Ntmdg","business_id":"vHz2RLtfUMVRPFmd7VBEHA","stars":5.0,"useful":6,"funny":2,"cool":2,"text":"If you follow me on Yelp, you'll see that I'm not the same foodie as I was 10 years ago. I lost my passion for gastronomy six years ago after eating at Alinea and wondering wtf I was doing with my life spending hundreds of dollars on terrible food. Don't get me wrong, I still love fine dining but on a daily basis, I no longer seek new restaurants to try, I'm no longer adventurous with food, and I only stick to places that are tried and true. Simply put, I've become a basic bitch.\n\nAll this changed over the weekend at Hell's Kitchen.\n\nI'm a huge fan of Gordon Ramsay despite having mediocre experiences at his namesake restaurant in LA (now closed) and BurgR over at Planet Hollywood. I don't even watch his TV shows, yet I love the guy. I was hugely disappointed to find out Serendipity was closing but very excited to learn that it would be replaced with Hell's Kitchen, a restaurant based on Ramsay's hit TV show of the same name.\n\nReservations for lunch were easily made a week in advance. We got there 30-minutes late, but I called the hostess earlier letting her know and there were no problems. We were seated within 10-minutes.\n\nWe were told the restaurant is modeled after the set on the TV show, but my friend and I aren't fans so it meant nothing to us. However, they did a fantastic job renovating the space and it's gorgeous. You could see the devil in the details, on the columns, light fixtures, everything.\n\nHibiscus Sour - $8\nTea with lemon and simple syrup, this is one of my favorite drinks and they made it perfectly. I wish more places served this mix. I've only had it at one other place (Guisados).\n\nLobster Risotto - $25\nYES, YES, YES! This is a must if you like truffles and lobster. I was legit moved to tears, and my friend looked at me like I was insane. Everything about this dish was perfect. The risotto was soft and fluffy with strong authentic flavors of truffle. The butter-poached lobster tail was cooked on point, very fresh. I'm all about texture so the crispy onions were an added delight. I'd go back and just order two of these for my main entree alone.\n\nEggs in Purgatory - $19\nThis was mentioned a lot on Yelp and I hated it. Two poached eggs over sourdough toast sprinkled with feta cheese and soaked in spicy tomato sauce. To be fair, I hate feta cheese so would not recommend.\n\nPumpkin Soup - $14 (included in prix fixe)\nNot a fan of pumpkin but it was this or Caesar's salad as my choice of appetizer. I had two sips.\n\nBeef Wellington - prix fixe $75 for 6 oz. or $62 for 3 oz.\nThis was way, way better than the beef wellington I had in Ramsay's restaurant in LA. It was so good with the red wine demi-glace, but I was so full and could only finish half of it. Should've ordered the 3 oz instead because the other half is still sitting in my fridge.\n\nSticky Toffee Pudding - $11 (included in prix fixe)\nServed with speculoos ice cream, this is a must! It was surprisingly a large portion but it was so good, I easily finished 3\/4 of it by myself. The ice cream scoop could have been a lot bigger cos the pudding:ice cream ratio was definitely off, but it was so tasty, I didn't mind all that much.\n\nService was decent, no complaints.\n\nMaybe I haven't completely changed because I'm still eating junk food on a daily basis that all modern foodies would frown upon (lol); but Hell's Kitchen has helped reignite a small flame of passion for food again. I just can't wait to come back and get more of that lobster risotto and sticky toffee pudding!","date":"2018-10-11 02:59:31"}
